{
  "text": "Like [CITATION_1] , we found a positive correlation between follicular\u00afuid VEGF levels and follicular\u00afuid progesterone at the time of oocyte retrieval. This was observed in both groups. However, unlike [CITATION_2] , we also found a positive correlation between follicular\u00afuid VEGF levels and follicular\u00afuid estradiol levels in the control group. This was not seen in the coasted group. It is known that oocytes are lost during coasting, probably as a consequence of apoptosis of the granulosa cells followed by atresia of the oocyte. We might expect, therefore, to see higher VEGF levels in the follicular\u00afuid of coasted patients in follicles from which an oocyte was not retrieved compared to follicles from which an oocyte was retrieved. We do see higher levels but the differences were not found to be statistically signi\u00aecantly different. Unlike [CITATION_3] , we found no association between follicular\u00afuid VEGF levels and fertilization in either group. Interestingly, we did \u00aend signi\u00aecantly lower levels of VEGF in follicular\u00afuid from which oocytes were recovered which fertilized and cleaved to form grade 1 embryos compared to grade 2 and 3 embryos in the coasted group but not in the control group.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "30015403",
